    <text>
        <body><div type="bibliography">
                
                <p><bibl><ptr target="#oliverio1929"/>, p. 132, n. <citedRange>9</citedRange></bibl>, whence 
                    <bibl><ptr target="#SEG"/>, <citedRange>9.119</citedRange></bibl>;
                    <bibl><ptr target="#IGCyr"/> <citedRange>020600</citedRange></bibl>.</p>
            </div><div type="edition" xml:lang="grc" xml:space="preserve">
                
                <ab>
                    <lb n="1"/><persName type="attested" key="http://clas-lgpn2.classics.ox.ac.uk/cgi-bin/lgpn_search.cgi?id=V1-65142"><name nymRef="#Νῖκις">Νίκιο<supplied reason="lost">ς</supplied></name></persName>.
	 </ab>
            </div><div type="apparatus" xml:space="preserve">
            
                <p/>
 </div><div type="translation" xml:lang="fr" xml:space="preserve">
            <p><supplied reason="subaudible">Autel</supplied> de Nikis.</p>
            </div><div type="translation" xml:lang="en" xml:space="preserve">
            <p><supplied reason="subaudible">Altar</supplied> of Nikis.</p>
            </div><div type="translation" xml:lang="fr" xml:space="preserve">
            <p><supplied reason="subaudible">Altare</supplied> di Nikis.</p>
            </div><div type="commentary">
                
                <p>If this block is really an altar, it bears no god's name but the owner's name.</p>
	           <p>The stone seems to be now lost. Oliverio gave neither clue for the date nor photograph, so that a date in the third or second century BC
	               given in <bibl><ptr target="#SEG"/>, <citedRange>9.119</citedRange></bibl> is groundless.</p>
	<p/>
            </div></body>
